DescriptionString: DrugBank is the clinical development intelligence platform built for strategy, R&D, and portfolio teams focused on outpacing competitors and making faster, more confident decisions.
A controlled vocabulary for annotating gene products to pathways.

Uberon is an integrated cross-species anatomy ontology representing a variety of entities classified according to traditional anatomical criteria such as structure, function and developmental lineage.
The Cell Ontology is a structured controlled vocabulary for cell types in animals.
Morphological and physiological measurement records generated from clinical and model organism research and health programs.

The Experimental Factor Ontology (EFO) provides a systematic description of many experimental variables available in EBI databases, and for external projects such as the NHGRI GWAS catalogue. It combines parts of several biological ontologies, such as anatomy, disease and chemical compounds. The scope of EFO is to support the annotation, analysis and visualization of data handled by many groups at the EBI and as the core ontology for OpenTargets.org

NCIt is a reference terminology that includes broad coverage of the cancer domain, including cancer related diseases, findings and abnormalities. NCIt OBO Edition releases should be considered experimental.

The Taxonomy Database is a curated classification and nomenclature for all of the organisms in the public sequence databases. This currently represents about 10 ofthe described species of life on the planet.

Gene integrates information from a wide range of species. A record may include nomenclature, Reference Sequences (RefSeqs), maps, pathways, variations, phenotypes, and links to genome-, phenotype-, and locus-specific resources worldwide.

Medical Subject Headings (MeSH) is the National Library of Medicine's controlled vocabulary thesaurus. It consists of sets of terms naming descriptors in a hierarchical structure that permits searching at various levels of specificity.
The Gene Ontology (GO) knowledgebase is the worldâ€™s largest source of information on the functions of genes.
The Pfam protein families database is a comprehensive collection of protein domains and families used for genome annotation and protein structure and function analysis.
Disease names from the Disease Ontology (DO). These names may be used to specify pathologies.
InterPro provides functional analysis of proteins by classifying them into families and predicting domains and important sites.
The Cell Ontology is a structured controlled vocabulary for cell types in animals.
A structured classification of molecular entities of biological interest focusing on 'small' chemical compounds.
A structured and controlled vocabulary for the phenotypic features encountered in human hereditary and other disease.
Selventa-defined names of protein families. Each family represents a group of related proteins.
Selventa-defined names of protein families. Each family represents a group of related proteins.
List of named complexes that are frequently used and/or are well characterized such as the NFKB Complex.
HGNC Gene Families.

Rat Genome Database (RGD) approved gene symbols. These symbols may be used to specify rat gene, RNA, microRNA and protein abundances. Single character encoding following each value specify which abundance types are valid.
Mouse Genome Informatics (MGI) approved gene symbols. These symbols may be used to specify mouse gene, RNA, microRNA and protein abundances.
An ontology for Alzheimer's disease research.
An ontology representing brain region cell types.
organize the knowledge domain of measured brain features in association with neurodegenerative diseases by imaging technologies.

NameString: Human Genome Organisation (HUGO) Gene Nomenclature Committee
DescriptionString: Human Genome Organisation (HUGO) Gene Nomenclature Committee at the European Bioinformatics Institute approves a gene name and symbol (short-form abbreviation) for each known human gene. All approved symbols are stored in the HGNC database.
